references: In this section, we study how the bargaining cost affects the results of the proposed approach. We are interested in two situations: when the cost is linear to the bargaining rounds and when it is exponential to the bargaining rounds, i.e., Câ€‹(T)=aâ€‹Tğ¶ğ‘‡ğ‘ğ‘‡C(T)=aT and 2) Câ€‹(T)=aTğ¶ğ‘‡superscriptğ‘ğ‘‡C(T)=a^{T}. We vary the cost factor ağ‘a and termination condition related hyper-parameter Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon in Section 3.4.3 to further analyze the effect of bargaining cost. For simplicity, we set 10âˆ—Ctâ€‹(T)=10âˆ—Cdâ€‹(T)=Câ€‹(T)10subscriptğ¶ğ‘¡ğ‘‡10subscriptğ¶ğ‘‘ğ‘‡ğ¶ğ‘‡10*C_{t}(T)=10*C_{d}(T)=C(T) for the Credit and Adult dataset. We use Ïµd=Ïµt=Ïµsubscriptitalic-Ïµğ‘‘subscriptitalic-Ïµğ‘¡italic-Ïµ\epsilon_{d}=\epsilon_{t}=\epsilon for both datasets. We employ different Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon on different datasets, the one underlined is set as the default value. We run the bargaining 100 times and report the mean and standard deviation of the net profit, payment, and cost of the final bargaining state. Note that the net profit and payment are calculated as the revenue before minus cost. The results under Random Forest base model are illustrated in Table 3, and those of the original perfect performance information setting are also included for comparison. The initial states of the current evaluation are the same for all runs.

Table 3 shows that when cost is introduced to the bargaining model, the net profit, payment, and realized Î”â€‹GÎ”ğº\Delta G are all generally smaller compared to the No Cost version, which indicates the two parties tend to reach a less optimal equilibrium. Such a trend is more significant when the cost increases faster (i.e., larger ağ‘a), which makes long-term negotiation less tolerable. Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon also plays an important role in determining the final state of bargaining. It can be observed that a smaller Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon generally leads to higher revenue for both parties, as it indicates the final realized Î”â€‹GÎ”ğº\Delta G is closer to the target one. However, this also leads to higher bargaining costs, which might offset the advantage of increased revenue. Therefore, as a player, it is important to consider the trade-off between bargaining efficiency and better equilibrium during decision making in the feature bargaining.
